age_html": null}], "linkedin_post": {"text": "LINKEDIN POST:\n\nArmenia grew its online gambling market 35 times in eight years.\n\nThe parliament just passed a law banning pensioners, welfare recipients, and people in bankruptcy from all online casinos. One click of the mandatory self-exclusion button locks a player out of every licensed operator in the country for five years.\n\nThis is the regulatory overcorrection cycle that every fast-growing market eventually hits. Minimal oversight enables rapid growth. Rapid growth creates problem gambling data. Problem gambling data triggers sweeping legislation that hits legitimate operators harder than unlicensed ones.\n\nThe detail most VIP teams miss: these restrictions aren't targeted at high-value players. They compress the addressable player pool at the bottom - but they signal where the regulatory mood is heading for everyone. When a market that grew 35x starts defining who is allowed to play, the next question is how much.\n\nThe operators who avoid this cycle are the ones who build responsible gambling infrastructure while the market is growing - not after the parliament drafts the law.\n\nArmenia isn't a small-market story. It's a preview.\n\n#iGaming #VIPRetention #CasinoOperations #PlayerExperience"}}